\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
To express facts about someone in RDF triples, we need a property to define the semantic relationship between a subject and an object. For example, 'Henry / occupation / writer.' Several RDF vocabularies can be used to specify this relationship. It means that the nature of these vocabularies determines what can be express. \
\ls2\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Again, we have noticed some limits related to granularity. Thus, according to the vocabulary chosen, we were able to express that Henry Carton de Wiart was an author of a book OR we could precise he was the author of the preface. In a family context, depending on what vocabulary we used, we can precise someone is an uncle, OR just describe the fact that is a relative. In this case, we would loose details and have uncle and cousin described by the same vague property.\
\ls2\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
To sum up, the more precise is a vocabulary, the more we can express. For example in the field of social relationship, one vocabulary called 'relationship' allows us to qualify 'acquaintance of', 'friend of', 'a close friend of', 'lost contact with', 'has met', etc. However, sometimes it appears quite difficult to evaluate the specific nature of a relationship between two dead people... \
\ls2\ilvl1\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	
\f1 \uc0\u9702 
\f0 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
During the triplification process, most data has been translated in RDF triples without issues. In a few cases, we lacked vocabularies terms to express more atypical statements, such as details about his personality, or mentions about his activist activities in the context of social struggles. Obviously, it raises the question of the long tail\'85 to what extent should we create new properties for each specific case?\
